<DOC><DOCNO> AP880223-0045 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0726EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs 460   02-23 0476</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs, 460</SECOND><HEAD>Secretary Of State Says Weather Shouldn't Affect Voter Turnout</HEAD><DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Secretary of State Joyce Hazeltine says shedoubts that today's weather will affect voter turnout, and shestill expects about one-half the state's registered Republicans andone-third of the Democrats to vote in the presidential primary.   The weather forecast calls for strong winds but no snow, shesaid.   The secretary of state said the fact that Vice President GeorgeBush withdrew from active competition in the South Dakota primarywill not affect Republican voter turnout.   ``How I see that. Those who are for him are going to vote forhim anyway. Those who are angry with him for that are going to comeout and vote for (Bob) Dole.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Texas Kemp Camp Issues Invitation To Disgruntled Dole, RobertsonSupporters</HEAD><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of Rep. Jack Kemp's Texas campaign isasking supporters of Sen. Bob Dole and Pat Robertson to abandontheir candidates and join the Kemp campaign because of the refusalof Dole and Robertson to appear in a debate last week in Dallas.   Bob Holland, the Kemp official, call the action by Robertson andDole a snub of Texas.   ``By their failure to face George Bush in one of his home statesFriday night, Bob Dole made clear that he has written off Texas andPat Robertson committed another serious blunder casting furtherdoubts on his electability,'' Holland said.   The withdrawals left only Kemp and Bush to debate.   ``We have had many disappointed former Dole and Robertson andfor that matter (Pete) du Pont supporters calling us looking for anew home and we want them to know they are welcome to join us,''Holland said.   Du Pont, former governor of Delaware, withdrew last week as acandidate for the Republican nomination.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>State Phones May Have Been Used to Aid Gore Campaign</HEAD><DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Agriculture Commissioner Ward ``Butch''Burnette said 32 calls from his department's phones to supportersof the presidential campaign of U.S. Sen. Albert Gore Jr. were madeto discuss official business, not the Democrat's race.   Burnette, Gore's Kentucky campaign chairman, and two of hisaides involved in the campaign said the campaign may have come up,though.   Burnette said six calls to Gore headquarters in Arlington, Va.,were made to clarify news reports published locally Jan. 19 aboutthe Tennessee senator's agriculture platform. The calls were made,however, Jan. 12-14, according to The Courier-Journal.   The newspaper reported in today's editions that more than 70calls were made in December and January from state-governmenttelephones to offices and supporters of Gore.   The total cost of the 73 calls was $58.97, not including tax.   The day he was named Gore's state chairman, Burnette said, heissued a memo to employees telling them not to use state facilitieson Gore's behalf.</TEXT></DOC>